---
description: Capture a transferable study topic when the user asks what something is, how or why it works, or how two concepts differ (any language).
alwaysApply: false
---

When the user message shows a conceptual gap, capture one transferable study
topic. Do not announce the classification unless asked.

## Detect `concept_gap`
Intent (any language): definition, how it works, why it exists / why it
matters, or how A differs from B — without pointing at a repo file, module,
path, or symbol.

If the question is about this codebase (`repo_local`), answer from the code and
do not queue. If it is an execution request (`agent_task`), just do the work.

## Capture
1. Explain at the right level, with one concrete example.
2. Select at most **one** main transferable topic for this turn.
3. Persist a `want` (do not skip):

   ```bash
   python3 ~/.cursor/learning/cli.py want --topic "TOPIC" --note "why"
   ```

   If the CLI is missing, emit a final-line marker:
   `<!-- LEARNING-WANT topic="TOPIC" note="why" -->`
4. Confirm with one line after a successful write.

## Anti-noise
- Skip topics already in the queue or recently covered (CLI dedupes).
- Do not log bare generics (code, file, error…) or bare base languages
  (Python, JS…). Tools, frameworks, and protocols are fine.
- Repo jargon with no transferable concept → `repo_local`.

## Teaching extras
Recommend material only if the topic is new/fundamental or the user asks —
at most 1–2 specific sources (name + why). Never “search for X”.
For a curated track, route to `study-deep` instead of researching in chat.
